WEBVTT

00:00:00.879 --> 00:00:01.580
Hey, Sheena.

00:00:02.899 --> 00:00:03.900
Hey, how's it going?

00:00:04.320 --> 00:00:06.720
It's going really well. Looking forward to doing a show together.

00:00:07.040 --> 00:00:10.160
Thanks for everyone who's here on the live stream or watching that later.

00:00:11.240 --> 00:00:14.580
And with that, Sheena, welcome to Talk Python To Me.

00:00:15.559 --> 00:00:17.240
Thanks so much. Happy to be here.

00:00:18.100 --> 00:00:19.520
Yeah, I'm happy to have you here.

00:00:20.380 --> 00:00:22.420
We've got an awesome topic queued up.

00:00:22.860 --> 00:00:27.080
One that I just, I don't know if I'll ever get tired of coming back to this

00:00:27.100 --> 00:00:32.520
because I'm just such a fan of simplicity and getting stuff done and not like,

00:00:34.180 --> 00:00:36.680
let's see how many layers of things we can pile on.

00:00:36.840 --> 00:00:41.160
And by that, I mean, HTMX as a success story

00:00:42.200 --> 00:00:44.900
for going from a whole bunch of front end stuff,

00:00:45.590 --> 00:00:49.780
a bunch of different multiple apps, you know, JavaScript front end,

00:00:50.500 --> 00:00:53.980
Django back end talking to each other, but kind of being separate as well.

00:00:54.860 --> 00:00:56.000
And just switching to HTMX.

00:00:56.220 --> 00:01:01.680
You wrote up a really cool essay on this that we're going to dive into and share your experience.

00:01:02.800 --> 00:01:06.480
Yeah, it was a pretty fantastic experience overall.

00:01:06.800 --> 00:01:15.080
I was really surprised by HTMX when I came across it the first time because there are so many fashionable front-end libraries and frameworks.

00:01:15.360 --> 00:01:18.060
So when I heard about it, I was like, oh, it's another one of those, whatever.

00:01:18.920 --> 00:01:30.160
And then I went to a DjangoCon, I think it was 2022, and I saw a talk from Chris May, who's in the audience, and that got me excited about it.

00:01:30.460 --> 00:01:34.440
And yeah, that's kind of when my whole story started.

00:01:36.600 --> 00:01:47.280
So yeah, so what I had been doing before was working with, so I had this team and we were building a thing and we had a React front end.

00:01:47.300 --> 00:01:49.860
So on the front, and that's a normal thing.

00:01:49.960 --> 00:01:53.140
Like if you wanted like a modern front-end application,

00:01:54.280 --> 00:01:57.600
you'd use something like React or Vue or one of the many competitors.

00:01:58.400 --> 00:01:59.760
And then on the back end, we had Django.

00:02:00.440 --> 00:02:05.480
And I think that's like a fairly normal, fairly accepted way to do things,

00:02:05.780 --> 00:02:07.140
or it has been for a long time.

00:02:07.820 --> 00:02:11.480
But I think it's like, I think it's a little faulty.

00:02:11.620 --> 00:02:16.680
I think that front-end web development has been in a little bit of a complexity

00:02:16.700 --> 00:02:18.500
death spiral for the last little while.

00:02:19.160 --> 00:02:22.380
And sometimes it's useful, sometimes it's really helpful,

00:02:22.640 --> 00:02:26.640
but for some things you need certain tools

00:02:26.680 --> 00:02:27.780
in the front end, I think.

00:02:28.040 --> 00:02:32.800
But yeah, I think things have been going

00:02:33.260 --> 00:02:35.500
in the complexity direction for a long time

00:02:35.680 --> 00:02:37.620
and HTML solves a lot of problems.

00:02:40.040 --> 00:02:43.560
All right, well, you think back to the jQuery days.

00:02:44.220 --> 00:02:45.340
How did you use jQuery?

00:02:45.620 --> 00:02:51.580
You included a CDN or if you're wild, you might download it and include it in your own static content.

00:02:52.390 --> 00:02:53.880
And then you started using it, right?

00:02:54.500 --> 00:02:58.140
And just layers and layers have just been building.

00:02:58.270 --> 00:03:06.080
And JavaScript of 2024 era looks nothing like 10 years ago, 15 years ago, JavaScript.

00:03:07.480 --> 00:03:13.560
I would say it's one of the more complicated programming environments, you know, compared to something like C++, right?

00:03:13.700 --> 00:03:15.160
because there's so many steps in there,

00:03:15.200 --> 00:03:17.220
so many implicit linkings and stuff.

00:03:17.860 --> 00:03:19.780
Yeah, there's a lot of dark magic under the hood.

00:03:20.060 --> 00:03:21.340
It's very hard to know what's going on.

00:03:21.580 --> 00:03:25.540
And I think one of the challenges is that a lot of people

00:03:25.580 --> 00:03:29.320
used to get into web dev as their gateway drug to programming.

00:03:29.700 --> 00:03:30.900
Like they'd start off with web dev

00:03:30.960 --> 00:03:32.000
and then branch out from there.

00:03:32.080 --> 00:03:34.700
But now web dev is like this magic weird box

00:03:34.920 --> 00:03:35.580
with so many layers.

00:03:36.820 --> 00:03:40.720
And I think it's sort of messed a lot of people up.

00:03:42.220 --> 00:03:45.640
it's a challenge to get started in the way that people used to get started.

00:03:45.880 --> 00:03:50.760
And it's like the barrier to entry level programmers used to need to be here.

00:03:50.900 --> 00:03:51.860
And now it's here.

00:03:52.430 --> 00:03:56.640
And yeah, there's a lot of tricky things to the ecosystem as a whole.

00:03:57.160 --> 00:04:01.020
But yeah, like all the bold steps, all the magic things that happen under the hood.

00:04:01.110 --> 00:04:05.120
And the fact that you have to like tasks switch between completely different

00:04:05.400 --> 00:04:08.940
applications and completely different like ways of thinking.

00:04:10.180 --> 00:04:12.760
Like, so for me, I've always loved Django.

00:04:12.920 --> 00:04:13.500
It's so good.

00:04:14.720 --> 00:04:16.440
So with the thing that I was building,

00:04:17.200 --> 00:04:21.579
I went to Django because I needed to build the thing really, really fast.

00:04:22.820 --> 00:04:24.620
And so my efficiency was important.

00:04:24.860 --> 00:04:26.560
And then it was like, I need a good front end.

00:04:26.740 --> 00:04:29.640
And React was a clear choice at the time.

00:04:29.720 --> 00:04:33.100
But it means like switching, like for me to work on this thing,

00:04:33.100 --> 00:04:36.000
I need to keep holding the Django application

00:04:36.220 --> 00:04:38.380
and the React application in my head and how they talk.

00:04:38.480 --> 00:04:39.420
And it's not just React.

00:04:39.600 --> 00:04:42.980
It's like Redux and Saga and side effects and asynchronous goodies.

00:04:44.030 --> 00:04:46.720
And then on the Django side, it's all of that.

00:04:46.980 --> 00:04:51.260
And Django is, I think, much simpler to get your head around than React, actually.

00:04:52.320 --> 00:04:52.440
Yeah.

00:04:54.100 --> 00:04:55.380
Yeah, it's a tricky thing.

00:04:56.200 --> 00:04:57.880
Yeah, it definitely is a tricky thing.

00:04:57.990 --> 00:05:07.320
And one thing I would just like to put out early before we get too much mail is this is not necessarily a hate on JavaScript sort of thing.

00:05:07.380 --> 00:05:13.800
There are people in the node space that are super fans of HTMX.

00:05:13.980 --> 00:05:20.920
And I think what is not obvious about the benefits of HTMX, as we get into it, we'll talk about some of these things.

00:05:20.960 --> 00:05:22.140
But you were just touching on that.

00:05:22.700 --> 00:05:23.980
You've got this React front end.

00:05:24.040 --> 00:05:25.160
It has its own state.

00:05:26.040 --> 00:05:27.620
It also has its own capability.

00:05:27.780 --> 00:05:30.840
So it's running on the client side, so it can't talk to file systems or the database.

00:05:31.060 --> 00:05:32.300
It can only talk to APIs.

00:05:33.220 --> 00:05:41.100
On the other hand, you've got the Django app, which probably is not talking to APIs, but talks to the database, talks to the server levels things.

00:05:41.880 --> 00:05:45.280
And you've got to, as you're working on this app, think, OK, I'm in this context.

00:05:45.420 --> 00:05:46.320
That means no database.

00:05:46.540 --> 00:05:47.220
I'm in this context.

00:05:47.320 --> 00:05:48.780
That means primarily just database.

00:05:49.420 --> 00:05:51.760
And it's just you have these two worlds.

00:05:51.880 --> 00:05:54.800
And if you could say, could I just write in one of them?

00:05:56.200 --> 00:06:00.160
In the JavaScript, people might even pick like, I just want to stay in JavaScript, but always node.

00:06:00.820 --> 00:06:04.120
or always at least pick one of the styles of programming

00:06:04.700 --> 00:06:06.720
and not just constantly switch back and forth

00:06:06.890 --> 00:06:09.060
between these, you have browser capabilities,

00:06:09.110 --> 00:06:11.100
you have server capabilities, you have browser information.

00:06:11.440 --> 00:06:14.720
Like just, that is just not productive.

00:06:15.140 --> 00:06:16.840
It's not the best, right?

00:06:16.890 --> 00:06:19.220
And so as much as you can avoid that,

00:06:19.390 --> 00:06:22.800
and as we'll see, HTMX is super easy

00:06:23.040 --> 00:06:25.360
about keeping it in one place, right?

00:06:25.450 --> 00:06:28.079
So I think that's one of the big things

00:06:28.100 --> 00:06:31.340
that people should be honing in on as we talk about this?

00:06:31.340 --> 00:06:31.680
What do you think?

00:06:32.580 --> 00:06:33.260
- Oh yeah, definitely.

00:06:34.040 --> 00:06:36.240
Yeah, if I came across as hating on JavaScript,

00:06:36.680 --> 00:06:40.400
I dig JavaScript and I use it a lot where it's needed.

00:06:41.120 --> 00:06:43.800
I think it is a fantastic tool in the toolbox

00:06:45.160 --> 00:06:46.180
that I'm on sides with you,

00:06:46.220 --> 00:06:48.720
that it's just the complexity of switching contexts

00:06:48.820 --> 00:06:50.060
all the time, it slows you down

00:06:50.760 --> 00:06:52.340
and it's a lot to keep in your head.

00:06:53.720 --> 00:06:54.840
And so it's like, for me,

00:06:55.600 --> 00:06:57.419
when I was working on this application

00:06:57.440 --> 00:06:59.000
and needing to switch contexts all the time.

00:06:59.180 --> 00:07:02.020
It's like, you can't just make a thing.

00:07:02.420 --> 00:07:04.640
Like you have to like do the dance to make the thing.

00:07:04.980 --> 00:07:07.060
And it's like-

00:07:07.060 --> 00:07:10.080
- Set up four different chained file watchers

00:07:10.080 --> 00:07:12.320
to do their things and stuff, right?

00:07:12.320 --> 00:07:14.760
- So it just like adds a little bit of a,

00:07:14.760 --> 00:07:17.400
like you're slower than you would like to be.

00:07:17.400 --> 00:07:19.720
There's like more tedium than there should be.

00:07:19.720 --> 00:07:21.420
It would be nice if you could just like

00:07:21.420 --> 00:07:23.140
build the thing quickly in a simple way

00:07:23.140 --> 00:07:24.020
and it just works and is beautiful.

00:07:25.260 --> 00:07:28.920
And HTMX kind of allows that along with other tools.

00:07:30.300 --> 00:07:31.480
Yeah, so for me, that context switching

00:07:31.620 --> 00:07:33.380
was like a painful, painful thing.

00:07:33.930 --> 00:07:35.680
And for the team I was working with as well,

00:07:35.880 --> 00:07:37.380
I had a bunch of juniors on my team.

00:07:37.690 --> 00:07:40.900
And it was so hard to get them productive because it was like,

00:07:41.010 --> 00:07:42.600
OK, do you want to be productive on the back end?

00:07:42.700 --> 00:07:44.280
Or do you want to be productive on the front end?

00:07:44.780 --> 00:07:47.980
And then on the front end, that was complicated because of the,

00:07:48.350 --> 00:07:50.440
again, React, Redux, Redux saga.

00:07:50.680 --> 00:07:53.460
So they were all just like suffering.

00:07:55.319 --> 00:07:57.580
- And to put real features into place,

00:07:58.400 --> 00:07:59.800
you've gotta do a vertical slice, right?

00:07:59.800 --> 00:08:01.840
Which hits most, if not all, you know,

00:08:01.880 --> 00:08:04.720
you probably have to touch the React front end.

00:08:05.420 --> 00:08:05.760
- Yeah.

00:08:05.760 --> 00:08:10.020
- You probably need some new tiny bits of UI designs,

00:08:10.120 --> 00:08:14.120
you know, CSS and maybe some SAS build stuff there.

00:08:14.280 --> 00:08:17.740
And you know, like then you're doing the server side bits

00:08:17.740 --> 00:08:19.579
and then you're doing a database migration

00:08:19.600 --> 00:08:21.100
And it's just like it's end to end, right?

00:08:21.920 --> 00:08:22.020
Yeah.

00:08:22.340 --> 00:08:27.640
And for some people, it's not even reasonable to expect them to have all of those skills, those end to end skills.

00:08:27.820 --> 00:08:30.880
And then it's like you have to make your team complicated.

00:08:30.940 --> 00:08:32.820
You have to have a back end team and a front end team.

00:08:32.940 --> 00:08:35.300
And they need to now integrate with each other.

00:08:35.520 --> 00:08:39.140
And so it resembles the team stack.

00:08:41.639 --> 00:08:42.700
Yeah, that's interesting.

00:08:42.919 --> 00:08:45.260
Yeah, we have a group for this later, a group for that later.

00:08:45.380 --> 00:08:48.760
And, you know, look, if you're a huge company, maybe that actually makes tons of sense.

00:08:49.220 --> 00:08:49.360
Maybe.

00:08:49.500 --> 00:08:51.180
I'm not saying it does, but it may.

00:08:51.740 --> 00:08:54.720
But when you were a small company, it just doesn't, right?

00:08:55.080 --> 00:08:55.800
No, no.

00:08:56.899 --> 00:09:00.700
And yeah, like I think when you're building something,

00:09:00.800 --> 00:09:03.220
you do need to think about the team that's going to be building it.

00:09:03.540 --> 00:09:06.300
Their skills right now, the skills that they're going to have in the future,

00:09:06.460 --> 00:09:09.000
the skills that you're going to need to pull into the team in the future.

00:09:09.420 --> 00:09:16.400
And so it's, I don't know if it makes sense to, well, in my context,

00:09:16.620 --> 00:09:19.680
it didn't make sense to split up the team.

00:09:20.920 --> 00:09:22.340
If I had the tools to allow everybody

00:09:22.500 --> 00:09:24.520
to be in the same place from the beginning,

00:09:24.660 --> 00:09:26.180
that would have been freaking fantastic.

00:09:26.960 --> 00:09:27.160
Yeah.

00:09:28.660 --> 00:09:29.420
Yeah, absolutely.

00:09:29.720 --> 00:09:30.140
That would be awesome.

00:09:31.540 --> 00:09:32.480
So let's talk about,

00:09:34.319 --> 00:09:36.280
let's talk a bit about HTML.

00:09:36.420 --> 00:09:38.580
So we said, hey, we've been talking about this

00:09:39.440 --> 00:09:41.120
in sort of broad terms,

00:09:41.520 --> 00:09:43.060
but let's be a little bit specific

00:09:43.320 --> 00:09:44.340
and maybe you could tell us,

00:09:45.360 --> 00:09:52.040
What is this HTMX and why is it not just a different flavor of

00:09:52.320 --> 00:09:53.340
reactor view or something?

00:09:53.780 --> 00:09:55.320
Then maybe we could talk through a few examples.

00:09:56.300 --> 00:10:01.880
Okay, cool. The way I explain HTMX to myself is that,

00:10:03.860 --> 00:10:05.480
imagine looking at HTML.

00:10:05.780 --> 00:10:08.260
HTML is with us, it's going to be with us forever,

00:10:09.580 --> 00:10:11.580
maybe not forever, but for a very long time.

00:10:12.190 --> 00:10:12.780
What if we like?

00:10:12.840 --> 00:10:19.380
many attempts to replace it and they were all bad. Yeah. Yeah. So it's probably going to stick

00:10:19.600 --> 00:10:24.100
around for the foreseeable future and it's everywhere. And what if we could just augment

00:10:24.160 --> 00:10:31.300
it slightly so that it could do what we needed it to do in the modern web? Like since HTML got

00:10:31.520 --> 00:10:36.859
invented, like it's quite a simple tool, but now we need to do all this extra stuff because people

00:10:36.860 --> 00:10:43.280
expect all sorts of interactivity in the user interfaces. They expect asynchronous workloads

00:10:43.690 --> 00:10:50.420
and things like that. And what if HTML could do that? And it can do that. And it's not actually

00:10:50.490 --> 00:10:57.600
that hard to make it do that. You just need to add a few extra attributes. And so what HTMX is,

00:10:57.740 --> 00:11:05.560
is a really, really small JavaScript library. And you just include it as a script tag in your page,

00:11:05.800 --> 00:11:11.380
and then it's there and it's available and it's installed just like the old, the good old days

00:11:12.240 --> 00:11:16.660
of jQuery. Yeah, you could just go back and throw it in a CD if you wanted, couldn't you?

00:11:16.960 --> 00:11:22.500
That's right. I hadn't really thought about it. And then from there, you just have these extra

00:11:22.720 --> 00:11:30.280
attributes on your HTML tags that do different things. So for example, like, so HTML has a lot

00:11:30.280 --> 00:11:35.620
of different stuff, but if you were to like 80, 20 years and look at the parts that are the most

00:11:35.640 --> 00:11:40.060
used, then basically the stuff you'll use the most

00:11:40.220 --> 00:11:45.080
are like tying into events, like click event handlers

00:11:45.100 --> 00:11:45.500
or whatnot.

00:11:46.660 --> 00:11:49.620
And then when you click on the thing or whatever,

00:11:49.780 --> 00:11:52.380
it'll send a request to a back end.

00:11:52.760 --> 00:11:56.640
And the back end responds with an HTML fragment.

00:11:57.740 --> 00:12:02.220
And then you swap that fragment into your page somewhere.

00:12:02.820 --> 00:12:08.760
So if you were to look at the HTMX documentation,

00:12:09.320 --> 00:12:11.400
the hello world of HTMX is a button.

00:12:12.620 --> 00:12:16.520
And the button says, has the attributes HX post clicked.

00:12:17.660 --> 00:12:19.900
So it's saying, when you click on the button,

00:12:20.560 --> 00:12:24.760
then send a post request to a URL that's like forward slash clicked.

00:12:24.820 --> 00:12:27.980
So you can decide what HTTP method you're using,

00:12:28.540 --> 00:12:32.000
and where it's going, and what event you're tying into.

00:12:32.460 --> 00:12:36.560
And then when the response arrives, then you do something with it.

00:12:36.560 --> 00:12:37.720
And the response is HTML.

00:12:38.040 --> 00:12:42.800
It's not a JSON response that you then need to turn into HTML.

00:12:43.380 --> 00:12:46.040
It's plain old normal HTML.

00:12:46.190 --> 00:12:47.280
So it's super simple to write.

00:12:47.510 --> 00:12:51.240
And then you take that HTML and you put it somewhere on the page.

00:12:51.380 --> 00:12:54.600
So maybe you swap the current button

00:12:54.760 --> 00:12:57.160
that you just clicked with the HTML that was returned.

00:12:57.210 --> 00:13:01.640
Or maybe you take it and you put it at the end of another element.

00:13:01.920 --> 00:13:05.400
You can append stuff, you can pre-pend stuff,

00:13:05.860 --> 00:13:07.220
you can replace entire elements,

00:13:07.480 --> 00:13:08.920
you can replace the internals of elements.

00:13:09.700 --> 00:13:13.000
And that little pattern is actually really, really powerful.

00:13:14.820 --> 00:13:17.780
So, and you can tie into all sorts of different events.

00:13:17.990 --> 00:13:20.460
So there's like interacting with individual elements

00:13:20.660 --> 00:13:22.040
like a click or a form submission.

00:13:22.950 --> 00:13:24.880
You can say like on load or like on scroll

00:13:25.500 --> 00:13:26.860
or all sorts of different things.

00:13:27.040 --> 00:13:29.100
So events, yeah.

00:13:29.240 --> 00:13:29.800
- Yeah, absolutely.

00:13:30.140 --> 00:13:36.660
So one of the motivations that Carl, Carson Gross puts there is why should a

00:13:36.760 --> 00:13:38.880
and forum only be able to make HTTP requests?

00:13:39.150 --> 00:13:44.260
Why should you only be able to click and have click and submit events,

00:13:44.480 --> 00:13:45.100
trigger them, right.

00:13:45.220 --> 00:13:50.680
And all these things, you know, so it's kind of like just extending some of

00:13:50.690 --> 00:13:51.700
these niche features.

00:13:52.300 --> 00:13:58.160
Like you can click a button, but not an image in HTML to, to all the pieces.

00:13:59.420 --> 00:14:02.400
And then like you said, exchanging fragments of HTML, right?

00:14:02.600 --> 00:14:04.980
Like just instead of sending JSON back

00:14:05.260 --> 00:14:07.380
and then having the client side turn that into HTML,

00:14:07.490 --> 00:14:10.400
just do it on the server and stick it where it goes, right?

00:14:10.860 --> 00:14:11.600
Basically that's it.

00:14:12.280 --> 00:14:15.420
- Yeah, so it's dead simple to code as well,

00:14:15.490 --> 00:14:16.780
which is fantastic.

00:14:17.090 --> 00:14:17.640
So it's a simple,

00:14:18.800 --> 00:14:21.900
you're just server side rendering some HTML

00:14:23.660 --> 00:14:25.140
like we used to a long time ago.

00:14:25.330 --> 00:14:27.540
So it feels very familiar to people

00:14:27.560 --> 00:14:29.040
who got into web dev a long time ago.

00:14:30.559 --> 00:14:33.360
And the code itself is very, very easy to write.

00:14:33.580 --> 00:14:35.580
Like initially you might like scratch your head,

00:14:35.680 --> 00:14:39.480
unfamiliar, but give yourself a couple of hours

00:14:39.780 --> 00:14:41.080
and it'll start to feel familiar.

00:14:42.240 --> 00:14:44.340
It's, yeah, it's lovely to work in.

00:14:45.579 --> 00:14:47.560
- Yeah, I would also encourage people

00:14:47.620 --> 00:14:49.600
