00:30:55.899 --> 00:30:58.220
- Right, tell the Django people, what does this do?

00:30:58.250 --> 00:31:01.800
Like why do you need Django template partials

00:31:01.990 --> 00:31:03.520
instead of just Django templates?

00:31:04.880 --> 00:31:08.080
So it's just about organizing your code in a way that's a bit cleaner.

00:31:08.320 --> 00:31:12.260
So if you think about how you would render templates from your different views, if you

00:31:12.380 --> 00:31:19.160
had like a main page and then that page had a bunch of HTML things happening that made

00:31:19.280 --> 00:31:24.220
calls to the back end to different views and those different views use different templates,

00:31:25.040 --> 00:31:29.560
then even though all those templates are associated with the same page, it kind of ends up being

00:31:29.700 --> 00:31:30.380
a bit of a mess.

00:31:30.400 --> 00:31:33.300
You've got like a lot of different like partial templates.

00:31:33.440 --> 00:31:35.860
Now you need a cool naming convention for that.

00:31:35.960 --> 00:31:36.700
Like is this a page?

00:31:36.860 --> 00:31:37.480
Is this a template?

00:31:38.360 --> 00:31:41.860
And it gets just a little bit messy.

00:31:43.600 --> 00:31:49.320
And you need to switch between files all the time to see what things are associated with each other.

00:31:50.360 --> 00:31:55.360
Let's say you've got like five pages and each of them have like five different partials associated with them.

00:31:55.440 --> 00:31:59.700
Suddenly it's a lot of files and you need to organize things somehow.

00:31:59.780 --> 00:32:06.940
So what Django template partials does is it allows you to like say you've got like a main page file

00:32:07.900 --> 00:32:15.080
to-do list, right? You could define a partial template for a to-do item within that same file

00:32:15.410 --> 00:32:21.040
and it won't get rendered until you say render this thing. So you can like when you render your

00:32:21.500 --> 00:32:27.060
template for the first time, you can just say okay, loop over the to-do items and use this partial

00:32:27.060 --> 00:32:32.080
in place and render the things and that's great but then the other thing that you can do is that

00:32:32.900 --> 00:32:40.740
you can like in a view you can you can choose to render a template but you can choose to render a

00:32:40.780 --> 00:32:47.660
partial within that template as well and so let's say you've got a like a little form that says add

00:32:47.660 --> 00:32:55.780
a new to-do list item then you'd submit that form and then the view would look for the partial

00:32:55.840 --> 00:33:02.020
within the page that you care about and it'll render that and so it just ends up being that

00:33:02.530 --> 00:33:06.740
like everything is tidy and together and it makes sense because like the to-do list items are only

00:33:06.920 --> 00:33:13.540
used in this page and those items are only used in that page yeah yeah yeah one of the big challenges

00:33:14.120 --> 00:33:21.620
that you'll quickly run into with this style this htmx partial exchange style is when you show the

00:33:21.480 --> 00:33:25.680
the page originally, you want just the server rendered version, which includes, let's say,

00:33:25.860 --> 00:33:31.920
your to-do items. So you need the HTML for the to-do items in the main page. But then when you

00:33:31.940 --> 00:33:38.300
make changes to it, you need a little fragment of that same HTML to put a new to-do item in there

00:33:38.460 --> 00:33:43.340
or to edit one or something. And if you're not careful, well, then you have multiple copies

00:33:44.360 --> 00:33:49.040
of those laying around and somebody updates the design for one, and then it doesn't update the

00:33:49.260 --> 00:33:53.160
the partial one that you wrote, which is a copy, it's not pretty.

00:33:53.290 --> 00:33:56.680
So finding a way for reuse like this Django templates partials,

00:33:57.420 --> 00:34:00.460
it's pretty required, I think, if you're going to stay sane.

00:34:00.780 --> 00:34:03.580
It's like functions are required to write code.

00:34:04.040 --> 00:34:05.460
It's pretty much like that, right?

00:34:06.380 --> 00:34:06.880
Yeah, yeah.

00:34:08.419 --> 00:34:09.020
Yeah, I think so.

00:34:09.050 --> 00:34:09.520
I think so.

00:34:09.720 --> 00:34:12.000
Like you can get away with just using like lots of files

00:34:12.490 --> 00:34:15.100
and you could keep things dry with lots of files,

00:34:15.340 --> 00:34:17.659
but it gets like, it's very spaghetti

00:34:18.159 --> 00:34:21.100
unless you put a lot of effort into organizing it

00:34:21.159 --> 00:34:22.760
and then keeping it organized

00:34:23.110 --> 00:34:24.179
because people will make PRs

00:34:24.200 --> 00:34:25.860
that do like all sorts of weird things.

00:34:26.879 --> 00:34:33.360
So yeah, it's like, it's not good to have to like monitor

00:34:33.639 --> 00:34:34.520
that everything's organized.

